		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">Despite the great success in recent years of synchroton x-ray difraction studies of surfaces, very few experiments have been directed towards the problem of interface atomic structure. This is surprising in view of the large penetration depth of x-rays which make interfaces accessible (in contrast to other probes such as electrons) and the importance of interface physics in a wide variety of situations such as grain boundaries and metal-semiconductor diodes.I here propose to study interface atomic structure by developing the techniques of surface x-ray diffraction. The experiments will concentrate on silicon-silicon bicrystal interfaces which are model semiconductor grain boundary interfaces and for which detailed theoretical models have been published. Use will be made of the relatively new technique of direct bonding for bicrystal manufacture and the x-ray diffraction studies will investigate the relationship between the chemical and thermal treatment and the structure of the interfaces.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
